ecution complexes that entangle Christians and Muslims today. Corrigan reveals how US churches and institutions have continuously campaigned against intolerance overseas even as they’ve abetted or performed it at home. This selective condemnation of intolerance, he shows, created a legacy of foreign policy interventions promoting religious freedom and human rights that was not reflected within America’s own borders. This timely, captivating book forces America to confront its claims of exceptionalism based on religious liberty—and perhaps begin to break the grotesque cycle of projection and oppression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aChristianszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aPersecutionxPublic opinion. 0aProtestantszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aReligion and international relationszUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aTolerationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTolerationzUnited StatesxReligious aspectsxHistory. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aUnited States.  aforeign policy.  aforgetting.  aintolerance.  amemory.  apersecution complex.  aprojection.  areligion.  atrauma.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226314099423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226314099.jpg  a978-3-11-069309-6  UChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  